  "prompt": "What is the principle behind rocket propulsion?",
  "response": "The principle behind rocket propulsion is Newton's Third Law of Motion, which states that for every action, there is an equal and opposite reaction. In a rocket, this is achieved through the following key steps:\n\n1. Propellant combustion\n- Fuel and oxidizer are mixed and burned in the rocket engine's combustion chamber\n- This creates high-temperature, high-pressure gases\n\n2. Momentum and thrust generation\n- The hot gases are rapidly expelled from the rocket's nozzle at very high velocities\n- As the gases are pushed backward, an equal and opposite force propels the rocket forward\n- The force of expulsion is called thrust\n\n3. Specific key principles\n- Mass is ejected at high speed in one direction\n- The rocket moves in the opposite direction of the expelled gases\n- The more mass expelled and the higher its velocity, the greater the thrust\n- No external medium (like air) is required for propulsion, allowing rockets to work in space\n\n4. Types of rocket engines\n- Liquid-propellant engines\n- Solid-propellant engines\n- Hybrid engines\n- Ion engines\n\nThis fundamental principle allows rockets to travel through space and overcome Earth's gravity by continuously expelling mass in the opposite direction of desired movement.",
